sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I746210
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This part was made in order to transfer the S. aureus oligopeptide-based quorum sensing system into a BioBrick-compatible signalling mechanism.
In the natural system, the signalling oligopeptide (termed AIP) is made from AgrD by the membrane-located enzyme AgrB. It is then detected by the membrane-located AgrC, which phosphorylates AgrA which then has DNA-binding activity and upregulates transcription of the promoters termed P2 and P3 in the agr locus. There are four known variants of AIP with different molecular structures and cross-inhibitory activity; this BioBrick generates group I AIP.
In this part, the AIP generating part [http://partsregistry.org/wiki/index.php/Part:BBa_I746001 I746001] is combined with the permeability device, [http://partsregistry.org/wiki/index.php/Part:BBa_I746201 I746201], so that the AIP produced is able to leave the periplasm of the cell.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Narin Hengrung
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The AIP generating parts were synthesised by DNA 2.0 The permeability device uses a mutant protein supplied by Dr P.E. Klebba.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0010
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional terminator consisting of a 64 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I746200
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: FepA L8T Mutant - Large Diffusion pore for E. coli outer membrane.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: FepA is an outer membrane receptor protein for Escherichia coli involved in the uptake of the ferric enterobactin siderophore. This part is a deletion mutant of the wild type FepA, which has been shown to convert the protein into an open diffusion channel, similar to a porin. It allows larger molecules through than normally would be permitted.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Narin Hengrung
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The mutants were developed by Dr Salete Newton working in Professor P. Klebba's lab at the university of Oklahoma. They were kindly sent to us by Professor Klebba.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The original mutants had an EcoR1 restriction site within their coding sequence. This had to be removed via site directed mutagenesis, using a megaprimer based method.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I746000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This part was made in order to transfer the S. aureus oligopeptide-based quorum sensing system into a BioBirck-compatible signalling mechanism.
In the natural system, the signalling oligopeptide (termed AIP) is made from AgrD by the membrane-located enzyme AgrB. It is then detected by the membrane-located AgrC, which phosphorylates AgrA which then has DNA-binding activity and upregulates transcription of the promoters termed P2 and P3 in the ''agr'' locus. There are four known variants of AIP with different molecular structures and cross-inhibitory activity; this BioBrick generates group I AIP.
This part contains the coding regions for group I agrB and agrD (in that order), prefixed by the B0034 RBS and separated by a SaII site.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: David Wyatt
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The original sequences for agrB and agrD were taken from the S Aureus Sequencing Project at Oklahoma University (http://www.genome.ou.edu/staph.html). The sequences were then codon-optimised for E. coli using GeneDesigner from DNA2.0 (http://www.dna20.com), and then synthesised by that company.
